issue.title: Consider restructuring replication
issue.body:
Currently, replication is split across multiple jobs. A failure in a job can be difficult to correct because it may require touching the DB and/or repeating other jobs.

For this ticket, we will propose restructuring replication. In particular, we will consider an approach that uses a single job per druids and version and that job will be retriable. Steps within the job that have already been completed, e.g., creating a zip or replicating to an endpoint, will not be repeated.

In addition to normal replication, cases to be considered include:
* Two versions created in rapid succession.
* Adding an additional endpoint for already replicated druids and versions.

issue.title: Current upload size limit of 100MB: document or refactor?

labels.name: question
labels.description: Further information is requested, label should be removed once answered

issue.body:
The current API we're using restricts each WACZ file to 100MB. We would need to use different API to be able to upload files >100MB.
We should either: document this limit and perhaps add a check in the UI to reject files >100MB OR refactor to remove this limit.

However, since this essentially allows unlimited uploads on a shared key, perhaps we *should* keep the limit for now, until we integrate support for allowing users to enter their own key / register with web3.storage / etc...

@SuaYoo @Shrinks99 @RangerMauve what are your thoughts on this?

> [standard] aims to save you (and others!) time in the same three ways:
>

> 1. **Automatically format code.** Just run `standardrb --fix` and say goodbye to messy or inconsistent code.
> 1. **Catch style issues & programmer errors early.** Save precious code review time by eliminating back-and-forth between reviewer & contributor.
>
> No decisions to make. It just works. ...

[Read more about standard](https://github.com/testdouble/standard). [Watch the standard lightning talk](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uLyV5hOqGQ8)

issue.title: Consider restructuring replication
issue.body:
Currently, replication is split across multiple jobs. A failure in a job can be difficult to correct because it may require touching the DB and/or repeating other jobs.

For this ticket, we will propose restructuring replication. In particular, we will consider an approach that uses a single job per druids and version and that job will be retriable. Steps within the job that have already been completed, e.g., creating a zip or replicating to an endpoint, will not be repeated.

In addition to normal replication, cases to be considered include:
* Two versions created in rapid succession.
* Adding an additional endpoint for already replicated druids and versions.

issue.title: Consider restructuring replication
issue.body:
Currently, replication is split across multiple jobs. A failure in a job can be difficult to correct because it may require touching the DB and/or repeating other jobs.

For this ticket, we will propose restructuring replication. In particular, we will consider an approach that uses a single job per druids and version and that job will be retriable. Steps within the job that have already been completed, e.g., creating a zip or replicating to an endpoint, will not be repeated.

In addition to normal replication, cases to be considered include:
* Two versions created in rapid succession.
* Adding an additional endpoint for already replicated druids and versions.

The current API we're using restricts each WACZ file to 100MB. We would need to use different API to be able to upload files >100MB.
We should either: document this limit and perhaps add a check in the UI to reject files >100MB OR refactor to remove this limit.

However, since this essentially allows unlimited uploads on a shared key, perhaps we *should* keep the limit for now, until we integrate support for allowing users to enter their own key / register with web3.storage / etc...

@SuaYoo @Shrinks99 @RangerMauve what are your thoughts on this?

issue.body:
## Why was this change made? 🤔

The `standard` gem manages Rubocop upgrades and maintains strong opinions on the Ruby style guide so that we do not have to. This is a spike to explore what it would look like to replace Rubocop with standard and begin to evaluate which is a better fit for our team.

> [standard] aims to save you (and others!) time in the same three ways:
>
> 1. **No configuration.** The easiest way to enforce consistent style in your project. Just drop it in.
> 1. **Automatically format code.** Just run `standardrb --fix` and say goodbye to messy or inconsistent code.
> 1. **Catch style issues & programmer errors early.** Save precious code review time by eliminating back-and-forth between reviewer & contributor.
>
> No decisions to make. It just works. ...

[Read more about standard](https://github.com/testdouble/standard). [Watch the standard lightning talk](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uLyV5hOqGQ8)

## How was this change tested? 🤨

CI

The `standard` gem manages Rubocop upgrades and maintains strong opinions on the Ruby style guide so that we do not have to. This is a spike to explore what it would look like to replace Rubocop with standard and begin to evaluate which is a better fit for our team.

> [standard] aims to save you (and others!) time in the same three ways:
>
> 1. **No configuration.** The easiest way to enforce consistent style in your project. Just drop it in.
> 1. **Automatically format code.** Just run `standardrb --fix` and say goodbye to messy or inconsistent code.
> 1. **Catch style issues & programmer errors early.** Save precious code review time by eliminating back-and-forth between reviewer & contributor.
>
> No decisions to make. It just works. ...
